{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015q8TqHmhSUm8xRuwPd5wFy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 23 Feedback\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→1 failure (1 real, 0 generated).\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Pattern 1: Complete extraction failure on multilingual headers with non-Latin scripts\n    10→\n    11→**Affected files:** real only\n    12→**Count:** 1\n    13→\n    14→### What happened\n    15→\n    16→| Expected | Extracted |\n    17→|----------|-----------|\n    18→| Smażona zielona fasolka | *(empty)* |\n    19→\n    20→The title \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" appears on line 1 — the very first line of the file. Yet the extractor returned an empty string rather than a wrong guess.\n    21→\n    22→### Why\n    23→\n    24→The file has an unusual multilingual header structure:\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→Smażona zielona fasolka        ← Polish title (line 1)\n    28→GREEN BEANS BORKEUM            ← English translation (line 2)\n    29→그린빈 볶음                      ← Korean/Hangul (line 3)\n    30→```\n    31→\n    32→The Korean Hangul characters on line 3 likely disrupted the extraction pipeline. The extractor may be:\n    33→- Failing to parse the document at all when non-Latin scripts appear in the opening lines, returning empty instead of a best-guess\n    34→- Treating the trilingual preamble as ambiguous and declining to commit to any candidate\n    35→\n    36→The root cause is not a bad title choice — it is a complete failure to extract anything. The correct title was trivially available on line 1. The extractor should degrade gracefully by returning the first non-empty line when normal heuristics fail.\n    37→\n    38→### Recommendation\n    39→\n    40→Add a fallback: if the primary extraction logic returns empty (or null), return the first non-blank line of the input. This would fix this case with no risk of regression on well-formed files.\n    41→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"to