{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_012i4j6TsPBSg82yCBivnqLo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01U2CMNmLhtw4SQdT4hvGyaW","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2638,"cache_read_input_tokens":78737,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2638,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015ygKBPCmwC1T2xezVmc3V5","session_id":"93fcd165-c384-4cf1-b48c-241fa9498df5","uuid":"a1ae8c97-a6d5-415c-bb6d-48491e5b252a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CtJ5M436wxd4mkVvtwKMgC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 22 → 23: Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→40 generated-file failures, 0 real-file failures. The core algorithm works for real scanned pages. The generated files expose 8 failure patterns, of which 4 are likely to manifest in real-world data (OCR normalization, section headers, multi-line titles, single-word titles). The remaining 4 are synthetic test artifacts but still worth fixing for robustness.\n     6→\n     7→**Estimated impact:** 38-40 of 40 failures fixed (Pattern 8's \"title absent from file\" case may remain as an irreducible failure — returning `undefined` is the correct behavior there).\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Change 1: OCR Normalization Post-Processing\n    12→\n    13→**Fixes:** Pattern 1 (11 failures), partially Pattern 6 (5 failures)\n    14→\n    15→### Root Cause\n    16→\n    17→The extractor correctly identifies the title line but returns it verbatim with OCR corruption artifacts. There is no output normalization pass. Common substitutions:\n    18→- `1` → `l` or `I` (context-dependent)\n    19→- `0` → `O`\n    20→- `4` → `A`\n    21→- `¡` → `i`\n    22→- `€` → `E`\n    23→- `Í` → `I` (accent artifact)\n    24→- Stray trailing section markers (e.g., `+ SERVÍNG AND STORAGE:`)\n    25→\n    26→### Proposed Changes\n    27→\n    28→Add a `normalizeOcrTitle(text: string): string` function called on the final result before returning. This is a **post-processing** step — it doesn't affect candidate selection or scoring.\n    29→\n    30→**Location:** New function in `title-extractor.ts`, called at lines ~997 and ~1007-1011 (every return path that produces a non-undefined result).\n    31→\n    32→```typescript\n    33→function normalizeOcrTitle(raw: string): string {\n    34→  let text = raw;\n    35→\n    36→  // Step 1: Strip trailing section markers that got greedily attached.\n    37→  // Pattern: \" + SECTION_LABEL:\" or \" + SECTION_LABEL\" at the end\n    38→  // e.g., \"MAK0WIEC ZE ŚLIWKAMI + SERVÍNG AND STORAGE:\"\n    39→  text = text.replace(/\\s*\\+\\s*(?:SERV[IÍ1]NG(?:\\s+AND\\s+STORAGE)?|TOPPING|NOTES?|TIPS?)\\s*:?\\s*$/i, \"\");\n    40→\n    41→  // Step 2: OCR character substitution map.\n    42→  // Only applied to ALL_CAPS words or the entire string if it's ALL_CAPS.\n    43→  // For mixed-case text, substitutions are context-sensitive.\n    44→  if (isAllCaps(text)) {\n    45→    text = text\n    46→      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    47→      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")  // 0 before a letter → O\n    48→      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")  // 0 after a letter → O\n    49→      .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n    50→      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n    51→      .replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n    52→      .replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n    53→      .replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n    54→  } else {\n    55→    // Mixed-case: fix per-word\n    56→    text = text.split(/(\\s+)/).map(token => {\n    57→      if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n    58→      if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    59→        return token\n    60→          .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    61→          .replace(/0(?=[A-Z])/g, \"O\")\n    62→          .replace(/(?<=[A-Z])0/g, \"O\");\n    63→      }\n    64→      // Mixed-case word: 1 → l (lowercase L), 0 → o\n    65→      return token\n    66→        .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, \"l\")\n    67→        .replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"l\")\n    68→        .replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n    69→        .replace(/€/g, \"e\");\n    70→    }).join(\"\");\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  // Step 3: Title-case conversion for ALL_CAPS results.\n    74→  // Preserves Polish/French diacritics.\n    75→  if (isAllCaps(text)) {\n    76→    text = toTitleCase(text);\n    77→  }\n    78→\n    79→  return text.trim();\n    80→}\n    81→\n    82→function toTitleCase(text: string): string {\n    83→  const smallWords = new Set([\n    84→    \"a\", \"an\", \"the\", \"and\", \"but\", \"or\", \"for\", \"nor\",\n    85→    \"in\", \"on\", \"at\", \"to\", \"of\", \"by\", \"with\", \"from\",\n    86→    \"z\", \"w\", \"i\", \"ze\", \"na\", \"do\", \"od\", \"za\", \"po\",\n    87→  ]);\n    88→  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((word, i) => {\n    89→    if (/^\\s+$/.test(word)) return word;\n    90→    const lower = word.toLowerCase();\n    91→    // Always capitalize first word and words after separators\n    92→    if (i === 0 || smallWords.has(lower) === false) {\n    93→      return lower.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + lower.slice(1);\n    94→    }\n    95→    return lower;\n    96→  }).join(\"\");\n    97→}\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→### Before/After Examples\n   101→\n   102→| Before | After |\n   103→|--------|-------|\n   104→| `B4RSZCZ CZERWONY` | `Barszcz Czerwony` |\n   105→| `BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD` | `Beet Arugula Salad` |\n   106→| `B¡gos Śl¡wkowy z Bekonem` | `Bigos Śliwkowy z Bekonem` |\n   107→| `MAK0WIEC ZE ŚLIWKAMI + SERVÍNG AND STORAGE:` | `Makowiec ze Śliwkami` |\n   108→| `S01e with Brown Butter and Capers` | `Sole with Brown Butter and Capers` |\n   109→| `TOMATO LENT1L SOUP` | `Tomato Lentil Soup` |\n   110→\n   111→### Risk Assessment\n   112→\n   113→- **Low risk** — this is output-only post-processing; it cannot cause a previously-correct extraction to fail\n   114→- **Edge case:** A legitimate title containing a digit (e.g., \"7-UP Cake\") could be corrupted → mitigate by only substituting digits that are adjacent to letters, not standalone digits or digits in number sequences\n   115→\n   116→---\n   117→\n   118→## Change 2: Page Reference and Category Header Filtering\n   119→\n   120→**Fixes:** Pattern 2 (6 failures)\n   121→\n   122→### Root Cause\n   123→\n   124→Lines like `Page 42`, `Page 102 - SOUPS & BROTHS`, `Strona 65 - MIĘSA I WĘDZENIA`, and single-word category names like `VEGETABLES`, `FISH & SEAFOOD` pass `passesHardFilters` and score well due to position and ALL_CAPS bonuses.\n   125→\n   126→### Proposed Changes\n   127→\n   128→**A. Add page-reference patterns to `passesHardFilters`:**\n   129→\n   130→```typescript\n   131→// Page references: \"Page 42\", \"Page 102 - SOUPS\", \"Strona 65 - CATEGORY\"\n   132→if (/^Page\\s+\\d+/i.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   133→if (/^Strona\\s+\\d+/i.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   134→```\n   135→\n   136→**B. Expand `SECTION_LABELS` with English food category headers:**\n   137→\n   138→```typescript\n   139→// English — recipe-book chapter/category labels\n   140→\"vegetables\", \"seafood\", \"fish\", \"soups\", \"salads\", \"desserts\",\n   141→\"appetizers\", \"breads\", \"breakfast\", \"pasta\", \"grains\",\n   142→\"main courses\", \"side dishes\", \"preserves\", \"baked goods\",\n   143→\"fish & seafood\", \"soups & broths\", \"desserts & baked goods\",\n   144→\"meats\", \"poultry\", \"game\",\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→Note: Many of these are already present in Polish. The English equivalents are missing.\n   148→\n   149→**C. Add compound category patterns to hard filters:**\n   150→\n   151→```typescript\n   152→// Compound category headers: \"FISH & SEAFOOD\", \"SOUPS & BROTHS\" (when standalone)\n   153→// These use the & separator which survives the 8-word filter but are clearly category headers.\n   154→// Only filter when the line is ≤4 words and all words are from a food-category vocabulary.\n   155→```\n   156→\n   157→### Before/After Examples\n   158→\n   159→| Before | After |\n   160→|--------|-------|\n   161→| `Page 42` selected | Filtered → picks `BAKED COD WITH HERBS` (line 18) |\n   162→| `Page 102 - SOUPS & BROTHS` selected | Filtered → picks `BRUSSELS SPROUTS AND BACON SOUP` |\n   163→| `VEGETABLES` selected | Filtered (section label) → picks `ROASTED ASPARAGUS WITH PARMESAN` |\n   164→| `FISH & SEAFOOD` selected | Filtered (section label) → picks `Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` |\n   165→\n   166→### Risk Assessment\n   167→\n   168→- **Low risk** — \"Page N\" is never a recipe title; food category names as standalone lines are always headers\n   169→- **Edge case:** A recipe literally named \"Page 42\" (extremely unlikely) → acceptable false negative\n   170→\n   171→---\n   172→\n   173→## Change 3: Previous-Page Overflow Detection\n   174→\n   175→**Fixes:** Pattern 3 (2 failures)\n   176→\n   177→### Root Cause\n   178→\n   179→Files begin with a \"PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW\" or \"PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT\" block. The extractor treats these as the start of the document and either selects content from the overflow or gets confused by it.\n   180→\n   181→### Proposed Changes\n   182→\n   183→Extend `findBurstEnd` to detect and skip overflow preambles:\n   184→\n   185→```typescript\n   186→// In findBurstEnd, add a new check at the start:\n   187→// Overflow preamble: lines containing PREVIOUS/OVERFLOW/CONTINUATION/SPILLOVER markers\n   188→// Skip everything up to and including a visual separator (===, ---, blank line after marker)\n   189→const OVERFLOW_MARKERS = /\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i;\n   190→\n   191→let overflowEnd = 0;\n   192→for (let k = 0; k < lines.length && k < 30; k++) {\n   193→  if (OVERFLOW_MARKERS.test(lines[k].text)) {\n   194→    // Skip forward past the overflow block: find next visual separator or blank line cluster\n   195→    let m = k + 1;\n   196→    while (m < lines.length) {\n   197→      if (/^[=\\-]{4,}$/.test(lines[m].text) || lines[m].text.length === 0) {\n   198→        overflowEnd = m + 1;\n   199→        break;\n   200→      }\n   201→      m++;\n   202→    }\n   203→    if (overflowEnd === 0) overflowEnd = k + 1;\n   204→  }\n   205→}\n   206→if (overflowEnd > 0) i = overflowEnd;\n   207→```\n   208→\n   209→Also skip `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` bracketed markers from the Baked Cod file pattern:\n   210→\n   211→```typescript\n   212→if (/^\\[CORRUPTED\\s+SPILLOVER/i.test(text.trim())) return false; // in passesHardFilters\n   213→```\n   214→\n   215→### Before/After Examples\n   216→\n   217→| Before | After |\n   218→|--------|-------|\n   219→| `PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW:` selected | Skipped → finds `BEET AND GOAT CHEESE SALAD` (line 24) |\n   220→| `PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT - RECIPE FRAGMENT` selected | Skipped → finds actual title |\n   221→\n   222→### Risk Assessment\n   223→\n   224→- **Very low risk** — no real recipe title contains \"PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW\"\n   225→- This pattern is specific to the synthetic test generator, but the same logic would help with real multi-page scans where a scanner captures the end of the previous recipe\n   226→\n   227→---\n   228→\n   229→## Change 4: Remove Compound-Variant Title Stripping\n   230→\n   231→**Fixes:** Pattern 4 (4 failures)\n   232→\n   233→### Root Cause\n   234→\n   235→Lines 999-1009 of the current code strip compound titles of the form `A : B` when both sides share the same first word:\n   236→\n   237→```typescript\n   238→const colonMatch = result.match(/^(.+?)\\s*:\\s*(.+)$/);\n   239→if (colonMatch) {\n   240→  const [, first, second] = colonMatch;\n   241→  const firstWord = first.trim().toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/)[0];\n   242→  const secondWord = second.trim().toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/)[0];\n   243→  if (firstWord && firstWord === secondWord) {\n   244→    return first.trim().normalize(\"NFC\");\n   245→  }\n   246→}\n   247→```\n   248→\n   249→This was added to handle cases where `PIEROGI RUSKIE : PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM` should return only `PIEROGI RUSKIE`. But iteration 22's test expectations require the **full compound** to be returned:\n   250→- `LEMON CURD : LEMON CURD WITH THYME` → expected full compound\n   251→- `PORK CHOPS WITH APPLES : PORK CHOPS WITH MUSHROOM SAUCE` → expected full compound\n   252→\n   253→The stripping logic is also causing `HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)` to fail because the extractor falls through to a section header deep in the file.\n   254→\n   255→### Proposed Changes\n   256→\n   257→**Remove the compound-variant stripping block entirely (lines 999-1009).** The full compound title should be returned as-is. If a future iteration needs deduplication of compound halves, it should be done in the evaluation harness, not the extractor.\n   258→\n   259→Additionally, for `PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ` and similar `+`-separated titles: ensure the full line on line 1 survives as a single candidate. The issue here is that the extractor picks `WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ` from a section header deep in the file. This is also a Pattern 7 issue — the full title line at position 0 should win over distant section headers.\n   260→\n   261→```typescript\n   262→// REMOVE lines 999-1009 entirely:\n   263→// const colonMatch = result.match(/^(.+?)\\s*:\\s*(.+)$/);\n   264→// ...\n   265→```\n   266→\n   267→### Before/After Examples\n   268→\n   269→| Before | After |\n   270→|--------|-------|\n   271→| `LEMON CURD` (truncated) | `Lemon Curd : Lemon Curd with Thyme` |\n   272→| `PORK CHOPS WITH APPLES` (truncated) | `Pork Chops with Apples : Pork Chops with Mushroom Sauce` |\n   273→\n   274→### Risk Assessment\n   275→\n   276→- **Medium risk** — the stripping was added to fix a specific real-world case. Need to verify that the original `PIEROGI RUSKIE : PIEROGI Z MIĘSEM` test (iteration 18) still passes. If the test expectation was `PIEROGI RUSKIE` alone, it will break.\n   277→- **Mitigation:** Run the full test suite before committing. If the Pierogi case breaks, make the stripping conditional: only strip when the second half is an **exact subset** of the first (i.e., `B ⊂ A`), not when B adds new words.\n   278→\n   279→---\n   280→\n   281→## Change 5: Hyphen-Continuation and Improved Multi-Line Joining\n   282→\n   283→**Fixes:** Pattern 5 (4 failures)\n   284→\n   285→### Root Cause\n   286→\n   287→Four distinct sub-problems:\n   288→\n   289→**5a. Hyphen-broken words not joined:**\n   290→`ROASTED CHICKEN WITH ROOT VEGET-` / `ABLES` — the line ends with `-` but the caps coalescing doesn't merge because the first line has 5 words and >25 chars.\n   291→\n   292→**5b. OCR-corrupted ALL_CAPS not recognized as ALL_CAPS:**\n   293→`LEMON HERB RO45TED` contains digits, so `isAllCaps` returns `false` (the regex `line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\")` strips digits, but the remaining letters ARE all caps). Wait — actually that should work: stripping non-alpha from \"RO45TED\" gives \"ROTED\" which is all uppercase. So `isAllCaps(\"LEMON HERB RO45TED\")` should return `true`. The issue must be elsewhere.\n   294→\n   295→Actually, the real problem for \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" / \"VEGETABLES\" is that the caps coalescing requires `wordCount(line.text) <= 2` — but \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" has 3 words, so it's NOT eligible for coalescing. It goes through as a standalone candidate. Then \"VEGETABLES\" is also standalone. The 2-line join \"LEMON HERB RO45TED VEGETABLES\" should be generated — but \"VEGETABLES\" matches `isSectionLabel` (it's in the English section of SECTION_LABELS). So the join is blocked by `shouldBlock2`.\n   296→\n   297→**5c. Three single-word lines not coalescing into a title:**\n   298→`ROSEMARY` / `FOCACCIA` / `BREAD` — each is ≤2 words and ≤25 chars. But the coalescing code checks `!isSectionLabel(line.text)`. Is \"BREAD\" a section label? Checking SECTION_LABELS... \"pieczywo\" (bread in Polish) is there, but \"bread\" is NOT in the English set. So coalescing should work. The failure may be that the coalesced \"ROSEMARY FOCACCIA BREAD\" has a lower embedding score than \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" which appears later. Need to investigate further, but likely the structural heading bonus should help here.\n   299→\n   300→Wait — \"ROSEMARY FOCACCIA BREAD\" is 3 words, all ALL_CAPS with ≥4 alpha letters each. So `isStructuralHeading` returns `true`. It should get the 0.10 structural bonus. \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" — the trailing colon. Does `passesHardFilters` allow colons? There's no specific filter. But \"topping\" IS in SECTION_LABELS. After stripping the colon, `isSectionLabel(\"TOPPING & BAKING\")` — the set check is exact match, so \"topping & baking\" is not in the set. Only \"topping\" alone is. So it passes.\n   301→\n   302→Hmm, the issue might be that the caps coalescing produces \"ROSEMARY FOCACCIA BREAD\" at position 0, but then there's also \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" as a candidate... and the structural heading bonus goes to the wrong one. Or the coalescing might not be working because there are blank lines between the three words in the source file. Let me re-check: the file has `ROSEMARY\\nFOCACCIA\\nBREAD\\n\\nMakes 2 loaves...`. The `nonEmptyLines` strips blank lines. So indices 0, 1, 2 are ROSEMARY, FOCACCIA, BREAD. They should coalesce.\n   303→\n   304→The actual fix needed: the coalesced candidate should win. The issue is likely with scoring. I'll propose boosting position-0 structural headings.\n   305→\n   306→**5d. Partial line capture for split titles:**\n   307→`PLACKI` / `ŻÓŁTE` / `Z KUKURYDZĄ` → extracted `ŻÓŁTE Z KUKURYDZĄ`. The coalescing should merge all three if each is ≤2 words and ≤25 chars. \"PLACKI\" is in SECTION_LABELS (it means pancakes/flatbreads). So the coalescing SKIPS it. Then \"ŻÓŁTE\" and \"Z KUKURYDZĄ\" coalesce to \"ŻÓŁTE Z KUKURYDZĄ\". Fix: the coalescing needs a lookahead — if skipping \"PLACKI\" causes the remaining fragment to be meaningless (not a standalone title), don't skip it. Or: remove \"placki\" from SECTION_LABELS since it's being used as the first word of a recipe title.\n   308→\n   309→### Proposed Changes\n   310→\n   311→**5a. Hyphen-continuation pre-processing:**\n   312→\n   313→Add a pre-processing step in `buildCandidates` before caps coalescing:\n   314→\n   315→```typescript\n   316→// Join hyphen-broken lines: \"VEGET-\" + \"ABLES\" → \"VEGETABLES\"\n   317→for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length - 1; i++) {\n   318→  if (nonEmptyLines[i].text.endsWith(\"-\")) {\n   319→    const joined = nonEmptyLines[i].text.slice(0, -1) + nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n   320→    nonEmptyLines[i] = { text: joined, index: nonEmptyLines[i].index };\n   321→    nonEmptyLines.splice(i + 1, 1);\n   322→  }\n   323→}\n   324→```\n   325→\n   326→**5b. Relax caps coalescing word-count limit:**\n   327→\n   328→Change `wordCount(line.text) <= 2` to `wordCount(line.text) <= 3` for the first line in a coalescing sequence, so that `LEMON HERB RO45TED` (3 words) can coalesce with `VEGETABLES`.\n   329→\n   330→Alternatively, treat this as a 2-line join case and fix the `shouldBlock2` guard: \"VEGETABLES\" is a section label, but joining \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" + \"VEGETABLES\" produces a 4-word candidate that looks like a title, not a category header. Change the blocking condition:\n   331→\n   332→```typescript\n   333→// Only block join when BOTH lines are section labels, or when the join produces ≤2 words\n   334→const shouldBlock2 = isSectionLabel(line.text) &&\n   335→  (wordCount(joined2) <= 2 || isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(line.text)) &&\n   336→  !(wordCount(joined2) >= 3 && isAllCaps(joined2));\n   337→```\n   338→\n   339→**5c. Remove \"placki\" from SECTION_LABELS** (or move it to a conditional list):\n   340→\n   341→\"Placki\" starts real recipe titles like \"Placki Ziemniaczane\", \"Placki Żółte z Kukurydzą\". It should NOT be in SECTION_LABELS. The category label for this food group is \"naleśniki i placki\" (crêpes and pancakes), not just \"placki\".\n   342→\n   343→Similarly, review other SECTION_LABELS entries that commonly start recipe titles. Candidates for removal: \"placki\" (used in recipe names), \"ciasto\" (used in \"Ciasto Drożdżowe\" etc.). Move them to a \"category-only labels\" set that blocks single-word candidates but not multi-word joins.\n   344→\n   345→**5d. Add section-label-as-title-prefix heuristic:**\n   346→\n   347→When a section label word is immediately followed by non-label words on subsequent lines and all are ALL_CAPS, treat the label as the first word of a multi-word title, not a standalone section header.\n   348→\n   349→### Before/After Examples\n   350→\n   351→| Before | After |\n   352→|--------|-------|\n   353→| `VEGETABLES` (wrong line) | `Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables` (joined + OCR-normalized) |\n   354→| `ŻÓŁTE Z KUKURYDZĄ` (partial) | `Placki Żółte z Kukurydzą` (full 3-line join) |\n   355→| `TOPPING & BAKING:` (wrong) | `Rosemary Focaccia Bread` (coalesced correctly) |\n   356→| `ROASTED CHICKEN WITH ROOT VEGET-` (broken) | `Roasted Chicken with Root Vegetables` (hyphen-joined + OCR-normalized) |\n   357→\n   358→### Risk Assessment\n   359→\n   360→- **Medium risk** — modifying caps coalescing and SECTION_LABELS affects the entire pipeline\n   361→- **Mitigation:** Run full test suite including all 11 real files. The real files don't have these patterns, so risk is low\n   362→- Removing \"placki\" from SECTION_LABELS could cause a standalone \"PLACKI\" (as a chapter header) to become a false-positive title candidate — mitigate with the position-based scoring (chapter headers appear before the title)\n   363→\n   364→---\n   365→\n   366→## Change 6: Annotation Line and OCR Marker Filtering\n   367→\n   368→**Fixes:** Pattern 6 (5 failures)\n   369→\n   370→### Root Cause\n   371→\n   372→Generated files include a metadata annotation line `(OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)` that confuses the extractor. The parenthetical format causes `stripParentheticalGloss` to potentially interact badly, and the annotation disrupts the expected title-blank-ingredients pattern.\n   373→\n   374→Additionally, some files have `lngredients:` (with lowercase L instead of I) which doesn't match the ingredients section label detection.\n   375→\n   376→### Proposed Changes\n   377→\n   378→**A. Filter annotation lines in `passesHardFilters`:**\n   379→\n   380→```typescript\n   381→// Parenthetical annotations describing OCR artifacts\n   382→if (/^\\(OCR\\b/i.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   383→if (/^\\(.*corruption/i.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   384→```\n   385→\n   386→**B. Add OCR-corrupted section labels to detection:**\n   387→\n   388→```typescript\n   389→// In looksLikeIngredient or a new pattern:\n   390→// \"lngredients\" (OCR: l for I), \"lnstructions\" (OCR: l for I)\n   391→if (/^lngredients/i.test(text.trim())) return true; // in a new isOcrSectionLabel check\n   392→```\n   393→\n   394→Actually, better approach: in `isSectionLabel`, add OCR-variant matching:\n   395→\n   396→```typescript\n   397→// After exact match, try OCR normalization: replace leading \"l\" with \"I\"\n   398→const ocrNormalized = normalized.replace(/^l/, \"i\");\n   399→if (SECTION_LABELS.has(ocrNormalized)) return true;\n   400→```\n   401→\n   402→**C. Improve empty-result threshold:**\n   403→\n   404→For Pattern 6 files where the title is present but OCR-corrupted (e.g., \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"), the candidate should be found and selected. The issue may be that the embedding score for heavily corrupted text is too low. The fix is two-fold:\n   405→1. The OCR normalization (Change 1) should be applied to candidates BEFORE embedding, not just on the final output\n   406→2. Or: lower the minimum threshold for the first-position candidate\n   407→\n   408→Actually, a better approach: apply OCR normalization to candidate text before computing embeddings, then use the clean text for embedding similarity but preserve the original for output (which gets normalized in post-processing anyway).\n   409→\n   410→```typescript\n   411→// Before embedding:\n   412→const cleanText = normalizeOcrForEmbedding(candidate.text);\n   413→const embedding = await embed(cleanText);\n   414→```\n   415→\n   416→This ensures OCR-corrupted titles get fair similarity scores against the reference embeddings.\n   417→\n   418→### Before/After Examples\n   419→\n   420→| Before | After |\n   421→|--------|-------|\n   422→| `(empty)` for Braised Cod | `Braised Cod with White Wine` (found + OCR-normalized) |\n   423→| `TOPPING (optional):` for Drożdże Sernik | `Drożdże Sernik` (annotation skipped, title found) |\n   424→| `(empty)` for Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip | `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` (found + OCR-normalized) |\n   425→\n   426→### Risk Assessment\n   427→\n   428→- **Low risk** — annotation filtering is specific to synthetic patterns; OCR normalization before embedding is a quality improvement with no downside\n   429→\n   430→---\n   431→\n   432→## Change 7: Single-Word and Short Title Scoring Improvements\n   433→\n   434→**Fixes:** Pattern 7 (7 failures)\n   435→\n   436→### Root Cause\n   437→\n   438→Single-word titles like \"Golonka\", \"MAKOWIEC\", \"PROFITEROLES\" and short titles like \"Cheesecake z Jeżynami\" are under-scored relative to section headers that appear later in the file. The current bonuses:\n   439→- Single-word ALL_CAPS: +0.03 (vs +0.08 for multi-word)\n   440→- Structural heading requires ≥2 significant words (so single-word titles never get the +0.10 bonus)\n   441→\n   442→Meanwhile, section headers like \"PASTA MAKOWA:\", \"Chocolate sauce:\", \"Na masę:\" pass hard filters because they're not in SECTION_LABELS, and they score well on embeddings because they're food-related terms.\n   443→\n   444→### Proposed Changes\n   445→\n   446→**A. Expand section label detection for recipe-internal headers with colons:**\n   447→\n   448→```typescript\n   449→// Any candidate ending with \":\" is likely a recipe sub-section header, not a title.\n   450→// Exception: titles with \" : \" compound separators.\n   451→if (/:\\s*$/.test(text.trim()) && !/ : /.test(text)) return false;\n   452→```\n   453→\n   454→This is a powerful heuristic: recipe titles almost NEVER end with a colon. Sub-section headers almost ALWAYS do. Adding this single filter to `passesHardFilters` would eliminate:\n   455→- \"PASTA MAKOWA:\" → filtered\n   456→- \"Chocolate sauce:\" → filtered\n   457→- \"Na masę:\" → filtered\n   458→- \"Roasting:\" → filtered\n   459→- \"TOPPING (optional):\" → filtered\n   460→- \"GLAZE:\" → already caught by SECTION_LABELS, but this catches the pattern generically\n   461→- \"Parmesan cheese for serving Method:\" → filtered (ends with colon)\n   462→\n   463→**This single rule fixes 5 of the 7 Pattern 7 failures.**\n   464→\n   465→**B. First-line title boost:**\n   466→\n   467→When the first non-empty, non-metadata line in the document looks like a title (passes hard filters, is short, doesn't end with colon), give it a position bonus even if it's a single word:\n   468→\n   469→```typescript\n   470→// In the scoring pass, for position-0 candidates:\n   471→const isFirstTitle = rs.position <= 2 && wordCount(rs.text) <= 5 && !isSectionLabel(rs.text);\n   472→const firstTitleBonus = isFirstTitle ? 0.05 : 0;\n   473→```\n   474→\n   475→**C. For Mushroom Risotto specifically:** The file starts with continuation text from a previous recipe. The `findBurstEnd` prose-prologue detection should catch lines 1-3 (which are body text starting with lowercase/ending with periods). Once the overflow is skipped, the actual recipe content starts much later. This case may actually be Pattern 3 (overflow) rather than Pattern 7.\n   476→\n   477→**D. For Ogórkowa Zupa (empty result):** The title is on line 3 but the extractor returns empty. This suggests all candidates are below threshold. The first-line boost (B) combined with the colon filter (A) should fix this by eliminating competing section headers.\n   478→\n   479→### Before/After Examples\n   480→\n   481→| Before | After |\n   482→|--------|-------|\n   483→| `Na masę:` for Cheesecake z Jeżynami | Filtered (colon) → `Cheesecake z Jeżynami` (line 4) |\n   484→| `Roasting:` for Golonka | Filtered (colon) → `Golonka` (line 1) |\n   485→| `PASTA MAKOWA:` for Makowiec | Filtered (colon) → `Makowiec` (via OCR normalization of `MAKOWIEC`) |\n   486→| `Chocolate sauce:` for Profiteroles | Filtered (colon) → `Profiteroles` (OCR normalization of `PROFITEROLES`) |\n   487→| `Parmesan cheese for serving Method:` for Minestrone | Filtered (colon) → `Minestrone` |\n   488→\n   489→### Risk Assessment\n   490→\n   491→- **Medium-high risk for the colon filter** — some legitimate titles might have trailing colons in OCR output (e.g., a stray colon artifact). Mitigate by only applying the filter when the colon is clearly a section-separator (preceded by a header-like word).\n   492→- Actually, the risk is lower than it seems: if OCR adds a spurious colon to a title, the title line WITHOUT the colon would also be a candidate (from a different OCR read or line split). In practice, real recipe titles never end with colons.\n   493→- **Test thoroughly** with all 11 real files to confirm no regressions.\n   494→\n   495→---\n   496→\n   497→## Change 8: Minimum Confidence Floor\n   498→\n   499→**Fixes:** Pattern 8 (1 failure)\n   500→\n   501→### Root Cause\n   502→\n   503→For \"Sweet Potato Salad\", the title appears at line 29 — near the end of the file. The extractor grabs \"Salt and pepper\" from the ingredient list as a fallback. The empty-pool fallback at line 784 returns the first positional candidate regardless of quality.\n   504→\n   505→### Proposed Changes\n   506→\n   507→Add an absolute minimum score floor before the fallback:\n   508→\n   509→```typescript\n   510→// Replace the current fallback (lines 784-789):\n   511→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n   512→  const fallback = scored\n   513→    .slice()\n   514→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n   515→  // Only use fallback if the best candidate has a meaningful positive score\n   516→  if (fallback[0].rawScore > 0.02) {\n   517→    selected = [fallback[0]];\n   518→  }\n   519→  // Otherwise: return undefined (no title found)\n   520→}\n   521→```\n   522→\n   523→The threshold of 0.02 for `rawScore` means the candidate must be at least slightly more similar to \"recipe name\" than to \"ingredients/directions\" — a very low bar that legitimate titles easily clear, but random ingredient phrases fail.\n   524→\n   525→### Before/After Examples\n   526→\n   527→| Before | After |\n   528→|--------|-------|\n   529→| `Salt and pepper` for Sweet Potato Salad | `undefined` (correct — title not in extractable position) |\n   530→\n   531→### Risk Assessment\n   532→\n   533→- **Low risk** — the floor is very permissive (0.02). Any real title candidate would score well above this.\n   534→- Returning `undefined` is correct behavior when the title is genuinely not present in the scanned text.\n   535→\n   536→---\n   537→\n   538→## Implementation Order and Dependencies\n   539→\n   540→| Priority | Change | Files Modified | Dependencies |\n   541→|----------|--------|----------------|--------------|\n   542→| 1 | **Change 7A: Colon filter** | `title-extractor.ts` (passesHardFilters) | None — instant 5+ fixes |\n   543→| 2 | **Change 1: OCR normalization** | `title-extractor.ts` (new function + return paths) | None — instant 11 fixes |\n   544→| 3 | **Change 2: Page/section filters** | `title-extractor.ts` (passesHardFilters + SECTION_LABELS) | None — instant 6 fixes |\n   545→| 4 | **Change 4: Remove compound stripping** | `title-extractor.ts` (lines 999-1009) | Verify old Pierogi test |\n   546→| 5 | **Change 3: Overflow detection** | `title-extractor.ts` (findBurstEnd) | None |\n   547→| 6 | **Change 5: Multi-line joining** | `title-extractor.ts` (buildCandidates + SECTION_LABELS) | Depends on Change 2 |\n   548→| 7 | **Change 6: Annotation filtering** | `title-extractor.ts` (passesHardFilters + embedding) | Depends on Change 1 |\n   549→| 8 | **Change 8: Confidence floor** | `title-extractor.ts` (fallback logic) | None |\n   550→\n   551→Changes 1, 2, 7A are independent and provide the highest ROI. They should be implemented first and tested before moving to the structural changes (4, 5, 6).\n   552→\n   553→---\n   554→\n   555→## Expected Impact Summary\n   556→\n   557→| Pattern | Count | Changes Applied | Expected Fixes |\n   558→|---------|-------|-----------------|----------------|\n   559→| 1: OCR normalization | 11 | Change 1 | 11/11 |\n   560→| 2: Section/page headers | 6 | Change 2 | 6/6 |\n   561→| 3: Overflow preamble | 2 | Change 3 | 2/2 |\n   562→| 4: Compound truncation | 4 | Change 4 | 3-4/4 |\n   563→| 5: Multi-line joining | 4 | Change 5 | 3-4/4 |\n   564→| 6: OCR marker confusion | 5 | Change 1 + Change 6 | 4-5/5 |\n   565→| 7: Section header over title | 7 | Change 7 | 6-7/7 |\n   566→| 8: Title absent | 1 | Change 8 | 1/1 (returns undefined correctly) |\n   567→| **Total** | **40** | | **36-40/40** |\n   568→\n   569→The single highest-impact change is **Change 7A (colon filter in passesHardFilters)** — one line of code that prevents any colon-terminated string from being selected as a title. This alone fixes ~5 failures and strengthens the pipeline against a broad class of false positives.\n   570→\n   571→The second highest-impact change is **Change 1 (OCR normalization)** — a pure post-processing step that fixes 11 failures with zero risk of regression.\n   572→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015ygKBPCmwC1T2xezVmc3V5","session_id":"93fcd165-c384-4cf1-b48c-241fa9498df5","uuid":"fda48bb3-9cf7-4122-a88f-ec7773ec4170"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MEyBrTk7D1zyz6vtGvS2V8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 24 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→All 18 failures are on generated files. No real-file failures.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter in title — partial correction (4 failures)\n     8→\n     9→**Cases:** Beet Arugula Salad, Blackberry Fool, Chleb Pszenny Razowy, Lemon Herb Grilled Chicken\n    10→\n    11→**What happened:** The title was correctly identified as the first line, but OCR artifacts\n    12→(1→l/i, Í→I) were not fully normalized. The extractor returned the title with residual\n    13→corruption rather than the clean form.\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→\"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\"  →  \"Beet Aruguia Saiad\"   (expected: Beet Arugula Salad)\n    17→\"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"    →  \"Biackberry Fooi\"        (expected: Blackberry Fool)\n    18→\"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\" → \"Chieb Pszenny Razowy\"  (expected: Chleb Pszenny Razowy)\n    19→\"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\" → \"Lemon Herb Grilied Chicken\"\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→**Why:** The extractor is doing some normalization (e.g. lowercasing, stripping formatting)\n    23→but not applying consistent digit-to-letter substitution rules. `1` is sometimes converted\n    24→to `l` and sometimes to `i`, with no semantic check.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→## Pattern 2: OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor (5 failures)\n    29→\n    30→**Cases:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet\n    31→and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski\n    32→\n    33→**What happened:** The title IS the first line, but it's followed immediately by an\n    34→`(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation on line 3 and `lngredients:` (l for I) on line 5.\n    35→The extractor either returned empty or skipped to a random body line:\n    36→\n    37→```\n    38→\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n    39→\"Drożdże Sern1k\"               →  \"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\"  (serving instruction)\n    40→\"P1ern1k z Śliwkami\"           →  \"Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.\"\n    41→\"Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n    42→\"Żurek Krakowski\"              →  \"XxYyZz salt and pepper\"\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→**Why:** The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation and the garbage tokens throughout the body\n    46→(e.g. `XxYyZz`, `Podaw4ć`) are being misread — the extractor apparently discards the first\n    47→line as too corrupted (it contains digits), then fails to find a clean candidate, and\n    48→either returns empty or picks the first \"sentence-like\" string from the body.\n    49→\n    50→---\n    51→\n    52→## Pattern 3: Category/section header precedes the actual title (3 failures)\n    53→\n    54→**Cases:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n    55→\n    56→**What happened:** A non-title line appears before the recipe title — either a book-section\n    57→label (`FISH & SEAFOOD`, `VEGETABLES`) or a metadata bar (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...`).\n    58→The extractor misidentifies what follows as description, not title:\n    59→\n    60→```\n    61→\"FISH & SEAFOOD\" / \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" → \"In same pan, sauté shallots...\"\n    62→\"VEGETABLES\" / \"Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan\"      → \"Simple yet elegant vegetable dish...\"\n    63→\"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\" / \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\"   → \"\"\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→**Why:** The extractor treats the first prominent all-caps or pipe-delimited line as the\n    67→title, pushing the actual title into a \"description\" position that it then skips, ultimately\n    68→falling through to a body sentence or returning empty.\n    69→\n    70→---\n    71→\n    72→## Pattern 4: Title absent from the beginning of captured text (2 failures)\n    73→\n    74→**Cases:** Mushroom Risotto, Sweet Potato Salad\n    75→\n    76→**What happened:** The OCR capture starts mid-recipe — either mid-instruction or straight\n    77→at the ingredient list — so there is no title present at all:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→Mushroom Risotto: starts with \"Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock...\"\n    81→  → extracted \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n    82→     (title of the NEXT recipe in the same file)\n    83→\n    84→Sweet Potato Salad: starts with \"2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut...\"\n    85→  → extracted \"Salt and pepper\"\n    86→```\n    87→\n    88→**Why:** With no title available on the page, the extractor either picks up a later recipe's\n    89→title (the file contains multiple recipes) or grabs the first short phrase that looks\n    90→title-like.\n    91→\n    92→---\n    93→\n    94→## Pattern 5: Compound title with variation notation — only variation extracted (2 failures)\n    95→\n    96→**Cases:** HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION),\n    97→PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\n    98→\n    99→**What happened:** The full compound title is on line 1, but the extractor discards it in\n   100→favor of an internal section header from later in the file:\n   101→\n   102→```\n   103→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   104→  → \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\"\n   105→\n   106→\"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   107→  → \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→**Why:** The `:` and `+` separators in these titles may be triggering split logic that\n   111→treats only one segment as the title. The `--` prefix in the output suggests the extractor\n   112→is recognizing these as variation markers and outputting only the variation name.\n   113→\n   114→---\n   115→\n   116→## Pattern 6: Polish title + English subtitle on line 2 (1 failure)\n   117→\n   118→**Cases:** Golonka\n   119→\n   120→**What happened:** The first line is the Polish name, the second line is an English\n   121→translation/subtitle. The extractor skips both and returns an instruction sentence:\n   122→\n   123→```\n   124→\"Golonka\" / \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\"\n   125→  → \"Scatter vegetables around pan. + Sauce: Remove knuckles and vegetables from pan. ...\"\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→**Why:** The extractor apparently sees \"Golonka\" as too short or ambiguous, treats the\n   129→English line as a subtitle (not a title), and then falls through to body content. The `+`\n   130→separator in the output suggests the instruction-concatenation path was triggered.\n   131→\n   132→---\n   133→\n   134→## Pattern 7: Heavy OCR corruption in body with title on first line (1 failure)\n   135→\n   136→**Cases:** Placki Ziemniaczane\n   137→\n   138→**What happened:** The title `PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE` is cleanly on line 1, but the body is\n   139→extremely corrupted (`SKLADNIK1`, `d0 miałkuchu siatek`, `Sp|aszcz paіką`). The extractor\n   140→returned a corrupted body instruction instead:\n   141→\n   142→```\n   143→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\"  →  \"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\"\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→**Why:** Similar to Pattern 2 — pervasive corruption in the body may cause the extractor\n   147→to distrust even the clean first line and scan further, landing on a body sentence.\n   148→\n   149→---\n   150→\n   151→## Summary by impact\n   152→\n   153→| Pattern | Count | Affects real files? |\n   154→|---------|-------|---------------------|\n   155→| 1. OCR digits in title, partial correction | 4 | Possible — real scans can have digit/letter OCR errors |\n   156→| 2. OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor | 5 | No — annotation is synthetic test scaffolding |\n   157→| 3. Category/section header before title | 3 | Yes — cookbook pages often have chapter headers |\n   158→| 4. No title in captured text | 2 | Yes — page crops can miss the title |\n   159→| 5. Compound title with `:` / `+` variation | 2 | Yes — multi-recipe pages exist in real data |\n   160→| 6. Subtitle on line 2 | 1 | Yes — bilingual titles appear in real cookbook scans |\n   161→| 7. Heavy body corruption, clean title skipped | 1 | Possible — bad scan quality in real files |\n   162→\n   163→The highest-priority fixes for real-file robustness are Patterns 3, 4, and 5.\n   164→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015ygKBPCmwC1T2xezVmc3V5","session_id":"93fcd165-c384-4cf1-b48c-241fa9498df5","uuid":"662ae2de-5e86-4fea-8002-8b6a1dcd9bc0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U2CMNmLhtw4SQdT4hvGyaW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 24 → 25 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→18 failures across 7 patterns. The core issue is that the extractor's confidence model is\n     6→too fragile: it rejects plausible title candidates (especially OCR-corrupted ones) without\n     7→a reliable fallback, and its OCR normalization applies digit→letter substitutions without\n     8→considering what letter actually makes sense in context.\n     9→\n    10→The plan addresses failures in three layers:\n    11→1. **Pre-candidate OCR repair** — fix corrupted text *before* candidate scoring, not after\n    12→2. **Category-header bypass** — skip known non-title preamble lines before candidate generation\n    13→3. **Positional confidence floor** — trust the first plausible candidate more aggressively\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter — partial correction (4 failures)\n    18→\n    19→### Root Cause\n    20→\n    21→`normalizeOcrTitle()` runs *after* candidate selection and applies blind substitutions:\n    22→`1→I` in ALL_CAPS, then title-cases the result. But title-casing converts `I` to `i` in\n    23→non-initial positions, producing \"Aruguia\" instead of \"Arugula\". The function doesn't know\n    24→that `1` in \"ARUGU1A\" should become `L` (not `I`), because it has no dictionary or\n    25→context awareness.\n    26→\n    27→The fundamental flaw: **digit→letter mapping is ambiguous without word-level context**.\n    28→`1` can be `I`, `L`, or `l` depending on the word. Post-hoc substitution on the final\n    29→title string can't resolve this ambiguity.\n    30→\n    31→### Proposed Fix: Dictionary-guided OCR repair\n    32→\n    33→Replace the blind `1→I` / `0→O` substitution in `normalizeOcrTitle()` with a\n    34→dictionary-lookup approach:\n    35→\n    36→1. **Build a compact food-word dictionary** (~500 words): common English and Polish recipe\n    37→   words (ingredients, cooking terms, food names). Store lowercase forms.\n    38→   File: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n    39→\n    40→2. **For each word in the title**, enumerate possible digit→letter substitutions\n    41→   (`1→i`, `1→l`, `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, `¡→i`, `Í→i`). Check if any substitution\n    42→   produces a dictionary match. If yes, use that form. If no match, fall back to the\n    43→   current heuristic (positional/case-based).\n    44→\n    45→3. **Apply repair before title-casing**, so the casing step receives clean words.\n    46→\n    47→#### Before / After\n    48→\n    49→```\n    50→Input:  \"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\"\n    51→Before: 1→I → \"BEET ARUGULA SALAD\" → title-case → \"Beet Aruguia Saiad\" ✗\n    52→After:  \"ARUGU1A\" → try \"ARUGULA\" (dict match) ✓ → \"Beet Arugula Salad\" ✓\n    53→\n    54→Input:  \"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"\n    55→Before: 1→I → \"BIACKBERRY FOOI\" → title-case → \"Biackberry Fooi\" ✗\n    56→After:  \"B1ACKBERRY\" → try \"BLACKBERRY\" (dict match) ✓, \"FOO1\" → try \"FOOL\" (dict match) ✓\n    57→\n    58→Input:  \"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\"\n    59→Before: 1→I → \"CHIEB\" → title-case → \"Chieb\" ✗\n    60→After:  \"CH1EB\" → try \"CHLEB\" (dict match) ✓ → \"Chleb Pszenny Razowy\" ✓\n    61→\n    62→Input:  \"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\"\n    63→After:  \"GRILÍED\" → try \"GRILLED\" (dict match) ✓\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→#### Implementation Notes\n    67→\n    68→- Dictionary should be a `Set<string>` of lowercase words, loaded once at module init.\n    69→- For each candidate word, generate all single-digit and multi-digit substitution variants\n    70→  (bounded: max ~8 substitutions per word, max ~256 combinations for 8 digits — but in\n    71→  practice recipe words have 0-2 digit substitutions).\n    72→- To keep it fast, only attempt substitutions when the word contains a known OCR-artifact\n    73→  character (`0-9`, `¡`, `Í`, `€`).\n    74→- The dictionary doesn't need to be exhaustive — it's a positive signal (\"I know this word\"),\n    75→  not a negative one. Unknown words fall through to the existing heuristic.\n    76→\n    77→### Expected Impact\n    78→\n    79→Fixes all 4 Pattern 1 failures. Also improves Pattern 7 (Placki Ziemniaczane) where\n    80→\"SKLADNIK1\" → \"SKŁADNIKI\" would be recognized as a section label rather than noise.\n    81→\n    82→---\n    83→\n    84→## Pattern 2: OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor (5 failures)\n    85→\n    86→### Root Cause\n    87→\n    88→The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation on line 3 is correctly filtered by\n    89→`passesHardFilters`. But the *title line itself* (e.g., \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\")\n    90→contains digits that cause it to be rejected — not by `passesHardFilters` directly,\n    91→but by the embedding scoring. The OCR-corrupted title has poor semantic similarity to\n    92→the \"recipe name\" reference, pushing its rawScore below threshold. The extractor then\n    93→falls through to body text or returns empty.\n    94→\n    95→The secondary issue: `isLikelyGarbled` may reject some corrupted titles because\n    96→digit-interspersed words fail the vowel-ratio check or trigger the \"garbled word\" detector.\n    97→\n    98→### Proposed Fix: Pre-scoring OCR repair on candidates\n    99→\n   100→Apply the dictionary-guided OCR repair (from Pattern 1 fix) **before embedding**, not after.\n   101→This means candidates enter the scoring pipeline as clean text, getting proper embedding\n   102→similarity scores.\n   103→\n   104→Specifically, in `buildCandidates` or at the start of `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`:\n   105→\n   106→1. For each candidate text, apply the dictionary-guided repair function.\n   107→2. Store both the original text (for position tracking) and the repaired text (for embedding).\n   108→3. Embed the **repaired** text. Return the **repaired** text as the result.\n   109→\n   110→This also helps `isLikelyGarbled` and `passesHardFilters`: repair the text before\n   111→running filters, so \"1ngredients\" becomes \"Ingredients\" (→ section label → filtered),\n   112→and \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" becomes \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" (→ passes\n   113→all filters, embeds well).\n   114→\n   115→#### Before / After\n   116→\n   117→```\n   118→Input line: \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"\n   119→Before: Poor embedding → rawScore below threshold → empty result\n   120→After:  Repaired to \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" → strong embedding → selected ✓\n   121→\n   122→Input line: \"Drożdże Sern1k\"\n   123→Before: \"Sern1k\" → poor embedding → falls to body text\n   124→After:  Repaired to \"Drożdże Sernik\" → strong embedding → selected ✓\n   125→```\n   126→\n   127→### Expected Impact\n   128→\n   129→Fixes all 5 Pattern 2 failures. Also indirectly helps Pattern 7.\n   130→\n   131→---\n   132→\n   133→## Pattern 3: Category/section header precedes the actual title (3 failures)\n   134→\n   135→### Root Cause\n   136→\n   137→The three cases have different preamble styles:\n   138→\n   139→1. **\"FISH & SEAFOOD\"** — already in `SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. But the real title\n   140→   \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" (mixed-case, position 2) competes poorly because\n   141→   the structural heading logic finds no ALL_CAPS heading to anchor on. The extractor\n   142→   falls through to body text.\n   143→\n   144→2. **\"VEGETABLES\"** — already in `SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. Same scoring problem.\n   145→\n   146→3. **\"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\"** — filtered by `\" | \"` check. But then\n   147→   \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" at position 2 should be found as an ALL_CAPS candidate.\n   148→\n   149→For cases 1 and 2, the issue is that after the category header is filtered, the\n   150→mixed-case title at position 2 doesn't score high enough. There's no \"first non-filtered\n   151→candidate gets a position boost\" logic — the position factor only rewards position 0 in\n   152→the raw line array, not position 0 among surviving candidates.\n   153→\n   154→For case 3 (Ogórkowa Zupa returning empty), the pipe-delimited metadata line is at\n   155→position 0, and \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" is at position 2. The metadata line consumes line 0,\n   156→and there's likely a failure in `findBurstEnd` to skip it — or the ALL_CAPS title\n   157→at position 2 isn't getting enough structural heading bonus because position 0 is gone.\n   158→\n   159→### Proposed Fix: Candidate-relative position bonus\n   160→\n   161→Change the position factor calculation from raw line position to **candidate-relative\n   162→position** — i.e., position among candidates that passed hard filters:\n   163→\n   164→```typescript\n   165→// Current: position in raw lines\n   166→const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   167→\n   168→// Proposed: position among surviving candidates (0.0 for first candidate)\n   169→const candidateIndex = candidates.findIndex(c => c.text === rs.text);\n   170→const candidateRelativePosition = candidateIndex / candidates.length;\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→This way, when \"FISH & SEAFOOD\" is filtered, \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" becomes\n   174→the first surviving candidate and gets the maximum position bonus.\n   175→\n   176→Additionally, add a **\"first candidate after filtered preamble\" bonus**: when the first\n   177→N lines are all filtered (section labels, metadata, page refs), the first surviving\n   178→candidate should get an explicit bonus (e.g., +0.08) because it occupies the structural\n   179→\"title position\" in the document.\n   180→\n   181→#### Before / After\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→\"FISH & SEAFOOD\" (filtered) / \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" (position 2)\n   185→Before: position factor = 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - 2/50*2) = ~1.11 — modest boost\n   186→After:  first-surviving-candidate bonus = +0.08, candidateRelativePosition = 0.0\n   187→\n   188→\"Lato | Zupy | ...\" (filtered) / \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" (position 2)\n   189→Before: structural heading bonus applies but threshold may be too high\n   190→After:  first-surviving-candidate bonus ensures it clears threshold\n   191→```\n   192→\n   193→### Expected Impact\n   194→\n   195→Fixes all 3 Pattern 3 failures.\n   196→\n   197→---\n   198→\n   199→## Pattern 4: Title absent from captured text (2 failures)\n   200→\n   201→### Root Cause\n   202→\n   203→When the OCR capture starts mid-recipe (no title present), the extractor should ideally\n   204→return empty. Instead:\n   205→\n   206→- **Mushroom Risotto**: picks up \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n   207→  — the title of the *next* recipe in the same file. These are ALL_CAPS structural headings\n   208→  that score well.\n   209→\n   210→- **Sweet Potato Salad**: picks up \"Salt and pepper\" — a short phrase that passes hard filters.\n   211→\n   212→### Proposed Fix: Detect title-absent pages\n   213→\n   214→Add a \"no-title confidence check\": when the best candidate's rawScore is below a minimum\n   215→absolute threshold (e.g., 0.05) AND the candidate is not in the first 3 non-empty lines,\n   216→return empty rather than guessing.\n   217→\n   218→More specifically:\n   219→1. If the file starts with ingredient-like lines or cooking instructions (detected by\n   220→   `looksLikeIngredient` or `looksLikeCookingInstruction` on the first 3 non-empty lines),\n   221→   flag the page as \"title-absent candidate\".\n   222→2. In this mode, require a higher rawScore threshold (e.g., 0.10) for any candidate to\n   223→   be accepted.\n   224→3. For the Mushroom Risotto case: the best candidate (\"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA...\") is\n   225→   at position 4 (deep in the file after body text) and the file starts with body text —\n   226→   the title-absent detection should prevent selection.\n   227→\n   228→#### Before / After\n   229→\n   230→```\n   231→Mushroom Risotto: starts with \"Reduce heat and stir...\"\n   232→Before: selects \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n   233→After:  first 3 lines are cooking instructions → title-absent mode → returns empty ✓\n   234→\n   235→Sweet Potato Salad: starts with \"2 large sweet potatoes...\"\n   236→Before: selects \"Salt and pepper\"\n   237→After:  first 3 lines are ingredients → title-absent mode → returns empty ✓\n   238→```\n   239→\n   240→### Expected Impact\n   241→\n   242→Fixes both Pattern 4 failures. Returning empty is the correct behavior when no title\n   243→exists in the captured text.\n   244→\n   245→---\n   246→\n   247→## Pattern 5: Compound title — only variation extracted (2 failures)\n   248→\n   249→### Root Cause\n   250→\n   251→The compound title \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   252→is on line 1. It should pass hard filters (the ` : ` exception for colon-terminated lines\n   253→exists at line 306). But the extractor returns \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\",\n   254→which looks like a section header from later in the file.\n   255→\n   256→Looking at the file: line 1 has the compound title, line 3 has \"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED\n   257→PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\". The issue is that line 1 has 10 words — exceeding the 8-word limit\n   258→in `passesHardFilters` (line 324). The exception `/ [+:&/] /` is checked, but ` : ` in\n   259→this title means `+` and `&` don't match. Let me re-read... the regex is `/ [+:&/] /` —\n   260→that's a character class `[+:&/]`, so `:` IS included. So the 8-word filter should be\n   261→bypassed.\n   262→\n   263→Wait — counting: \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   264→= \"HERB\", \"ROASTED\", \"PORK\", \"WITH\", \"MUSHROOMS\", \":\", \"PORK\", \"WITH\", \"CARAMELIZED\",\n   265→\"ONIONS\", \"(VARIATION)\" = 11 words. The check is `words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)`.\n   266→The text contains \" : \" so the exception fires — this should pass.\n   267→\n   268→But wait, the `stripParentheticalGloss` function strips \"(VARIATION)\" because the base\n   269→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\" is ALL_CAPS and\n   270→\"VARIATION\" is ALL_CAPS → the function keeps it (line 397: `if (isAllCaps(paren)) return text`).\n   271→So the full title should survive.\n   272→\n   273→The most likely cause: the line is > 80 characters. Let me count:\n   274→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\" = 77 chars.\n   275→Under 80, so it passes the length check.\n   276→\n   277→Re-examining: the feedback says the extractor returns \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\".\n   278→The `--` prefix suggests this comes from a line deeper in the file that starts with `--`.\n   279→Let me look at the actual file content more carefully.\n   280→\n   281→Actually, looking at the file again — line 1 *does* pass hard filters, so it enters the\n   282→candidate pool. The issue must be in the scoring/dedup phase. The line 3 candidate\n   283→\"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" ends with no colon issue... wait, it\n   284→ends without `:` at the end. But \"MAIN RECIPE:\" at the start — does this get filtered?\n   285→No, it's not a section label or metadata pattern.\n   286→\n   287→The dedup logic (line 1044): \"if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter one.\"\n   288→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" (from line 3, after stripping \"MAIN RECIPE: \") may\n   289→be a substring of the compound title. The dedup would keep the shorter one, destroying\n   290→the compound title.\n   291→\n   292→**This is the real bug**: the \"shorter wins\" dedup rule is designed to prevent\n   293→\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" from beating \"Pierogi Ruskie\", but it also causes\n   294→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" to beat the full compound title.\n   295→\n   296→For the PIERNIK case: \"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\" on line 1,\n   297→and likely \"WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\" or similar from a later section header.\n   298→The `+` exception in the 8-word filter should let the compound title through. But\n   299→if a sub-section header like \"PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\" appears later and is\n   300→a substring of the compound title, dedup kills the compound title.\n   301→\n   302→### Proposed Fix: Protect compound titles from substring dedup\n   303→\n   304→Add compound-title protection to the dedup step: when a candidate contains ` : ` or ` + `\n   305→(compound separator), it should not be removed by shorter-substring dedup. The compound\n   306→form is the intended complete title.\n   307→\n   308→```typescript\n   309→// In the dedup filter, skip removal if the longer candidate is a compound title\n   310→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   311→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   312→  // Protect compound titles from substring dedup\n   313→  if (/ [+:] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n   314→  return !selected.some(\n   315→    (b) =>\n   316→      b !== a &&\n   317→      aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n   318→      b.text.length < a.text.length\n   319→  );\n   320→});\n   321→```\n   322→\n   323→Also, add \"MAIN RECIPE\" to the filtered prefixes or metadata patterns so\n   324→\"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" doesn't enter the candidate pool\n   325→as a competitor. Pattern: `/^MAIN\\s+RECIPE\\s*:/i`.\n   326→\n   327→Similarly, lines starting with `--` followed by a section label (like \"--VARIATION:\",\n   328→\"--WERSJA\") should be filtered as structural sub-headers.\n   329→\n   330→#### Before / After\n   331→\n   332→```\n   333→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   334→Before: dedup removes it in favor of shorter substring → falls to \"--VARIATION: ...\"\n   335→After:  compound title protected from dedup → returned as-is ✓\n   336→\n   337→\"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   338→Before: dedup removes in favor of shorter substring → \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   339→After:  compound title protected → returned as-is ✓\n   340→```\n   341→\n   342→### Expected Impact\n   343→\n   344→Fixes both Pattern 5 failures.\n   345→\n   346→---\n   347→\n   348→## Pattern 6: Polish title + English subtitle on line 2 (1 failure)\n   349→\n   350→### Root Cause\n   351→\n   352→\"Golonka\" (single word, mixed-case) at position 0, \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" at position 1.\n   353→The extractor returns cooking instruction text from deep in the file.\n   354→\n   355→The `pos0Primary` subtitle suppression logic (line 891) fires when position-0 candidate\n   356→has ≤5 words and is followed by a longer mixed-case candidate. But the penalty (-0.15)\n   357→is applied to the *subtitle*, not to help the title. The real problem is that \"Golonka\"\n   358→itself scores poorly on embeddings (single Polish food word vs. English reference\n   359→\"recipe name, dish title\") and falls below threshold.\n   360→\n   361→The fallback logic (line 915-925) should catch this: when all candidates are below\n   362→threshold, it picks the earliest with rawScore > -0.05 for position ≤ 2. But \"Golonka\"\n   363→might not be the earliest candidate if it was somehow filtered or if \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\"\n   364→at position 1 has a better score.\n   365→\n   366→Actually, looking more carefully: \"Golonka\" should pass all hard filters and become\n   367→position-0 candidate. The fallback should pick it. The fact that the extractor returns\n   368→\"Scatter vegetables around pan. + Sauce: Remove knuckles...\" suggests something deeper\n   369→is wrong — possibly \"Scatter vegetables around pan.\" passes hard filters (it's a cooking\n   370→instruction but wordCount is only 4, and `looksLikeCookingInstruction` checks for ≥4 words\n   371→AND starts with cooking verb — \"Scatter\" is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`!).\n   372→\n   373→**Secondary bug**: \"Scatter\" (and several other cooking verbs) are missing from\n   374→`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`.\n   375→\n   376→### Proposed Fix: Two changes\n   377→\n   378→1. **Expand `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`** to include missing verbs: \"scatter\", \"score\",\n   379→   \"pat\", \"rub\", \"pour\", \"skim\", \"strain\", \"heat\", \"discard\", \"rest\", \"marinate\", \"wrap\".\n   380→\n   381→2. **Strengthen position-0 single-word title handling**: When position 0 has a single\n   382→   word that passed hard filters and position 1 has a plausible subtitle (2-5 words,\n   383→   mixed-case, not ingredients), treat position 0 as a high-confidence title candidate\n   384→   regardless of embedding score. This is a structural pattern: `[FoodName]\\n[English Translation]\\n\\nIngredients:` is a standard bilingual recipe layout.\n   385→\n   386→   Specifically: if the first candidate is at position 0 with 1-2 words, and position 1\n   387→   has a mixed-case line of 2-5 words that is NOT an ingredient or instruction, AND\n   388→   position 2+ starts with \"Ingredients:\" or similar section label, boost the position-0\n   389→   candidate by +0.15 (enough to clear any threshold).\n   390→\n   391→#### Before / After\n   392→\n   393→```\n   394→\"Golonka\" (pos 0) / \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" (pos 1) / \"Ingredients:\" (pos 3)\n   395→Before: \"Golonka\" has weak embedding → falls below threshold → body text selected\n   396→After:  bilingual pattern detected → \"Golonka\" boosted → selected ✓\n   397→```\n   398→\n   399→### Expected Impact\n   400→\n   401→Fixes Pattern 6. The cooking-verb expansion also helps prevent future body-text leakage.\n   402→\n   403→---\n   404→\n   405→## Pattern 7: Heavy OCR corruption in body, clean title skipped (1 failure)\n   406→\n   407→### Root Cause\n   408→\n   409→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" is clean ALL_CAPS on line 1. The body is extremely corrupted with\n   410→Cyrillic characters, pipe symbols, and digit substitutions. The extractor returns\n   411→\"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\" — a corrupted instruction line.\n   412→\n   413→The title should be found: it's ALL_CAPS, 2 words, at position 0. The structural heading\n   414→logic should identify it. But the body corruption may produce false-positive candidates\n   415→that score higher, or the heavy corruption may confuse `findBurstEnd`.\n   416→\n   417→Most likely: \"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" is correctly identified as a structural heading and\n   418→gets the +0.10 bonus. But \"SKLADNIK1:\" on line 3 looks like a section label after\n   419→OCR repair (SKŁADNIKI → section label). The instruction lines with Cyrillic text may\n   420→bypass `isLikelyGarbled` because they contain enough vowels in the Cyrillic portions.\n   421→\n   422→Actually, the simplest explanation: \"Sp|aszcz\" passes hard filters because `|` is not\n   423→explicitly filtered (only `\" | \"` with spaces is filtered). And the mixed Cyrillic/Latin\n   424→text has enough vowels to pass the garbled check.\n   425→\n   426→### Proposed Fix: Strengthen garbled-text detection\n   427→\n   428→1. **Filter pipe characters in words**: A word containing `|` (pipe) within letter\n   429→   sequences is OCR noise. Add to `isLikelyGarbled`: if any word contains `|` between\n   430→   letters, mark as garbled.\n   431→\n   432→2. **Filter mixed-script text**: If a line contains both Latin and Cyrillic characters,\n   433→   it's OCR corruption. Add: `if (/[а-яА-Я]/.test(text) && /[a-zA-Z]/.test(text)) return true;`\n   434→\n   435→3. **With the pre-scoring OCR repair** (from Pattern 1/2 fix), \"SKLADNIK1\" becomes\n   436→   \"SKŁADNIKI\" → recognized as section label → filtered. This removes a false positive\n   437→   that may have been competing with the real title.\n   438→\n   439→#### Before / After\n   440→\n   441→```\n   442→\"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\"\n   443→Before: passes isLikelyGarbled (enough vowels), passes passesHardFilters\n   444→After:  pipe-in-word check → garbled → filtered out\n   445→\n   446→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" (line 1, clean ALL_CAPS)\n   447→Before: competes with corrupted body text → loses\n   448→After:  corrupted body text all filtered → wins easily ✓\n   449→```\n   450→\n   451→### Expected Impact\n   452→\n   453→Fixes Pattern 7. Also improves robustness on any future files with OCR mixing scripts.\n   454→\n   455→---\n   456→\n   457→## Summary of Changes\n   458→\n   459→### New file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   460→\n   461→A `Set<string>` of ~500 common English and Polish food/cooking words used for\n   462→dictionary-guided OCR repair. Words are stored lowercase, without diacritics (for\n   463→OCR-resilient matching).\n   464→\n   465→### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   466→\n   467→| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n   468→|--------|----------|----------------|\n   469→| Dictionary-guided OCR repair function | New function `repairOcrWord()` | 1, 2, 7 |\n   470→| Apply OCR repair before candidate scoring | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, before embed calls | 1, 2, 7 |\n   471→| Candidate-relative position bonus | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, position factor calc | 3 |\n   472→| First-after-preamble bonus | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, after buildCandidates | 3 |\n   473→| Title-absent page detection | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, early return | 4 |\n   474→| Protect compound titles from dedup | Dedup filter block | 5 |\n   475→| Filter \"MAIN RECIPE:\" prefix | `METADATA_PATTERNS` | 5 |\n   476→| Filter `--VARIATION:` sub-headers | `passesHardFilters` | 5 |\n   477→| Expand cooking verb list | `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` | 6 |\n   478→| Bilingual layout pattern boost | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, new bonus | 6 |\n   479→| Pipe-in-word garbled detection | `isLikelyGarbled` | 7 |\n   480→| Mixed Cyrillic/Latin garbled detection | `isLikelyGarbled` | 7 |\n   481→\n   482→### Expected accuracy impact\n   483→\n   484→| Pattern | Count | Expected Fix Rate |\n   485→|---------|-------|-------------------|\n   486→| 1. OCR digits, partial correction | 4 | 4/4 (dictionary repair) |\n   487→| 2. OCR annotation confuses extractor | 5 | 5/5 (pre-scoring repair) |\n   488→| 3. Category header before title | 3 | 3/3 (candidate-relative position) |\n   489→| 4. Title absent from text | 2 | 2/2 (title-absent detection) |\n   490→| 5. Compound title truncated | 2 | 2/2 (dedup protection) |\n   491→| 6. Subtitle on line 2 | 1 | 1/1 (bilingual boost + verb expansion) |\n   492→| 7. Heavy body corruption | 1 | 1/1 (garbled detection + OCR repair) |\n   493→| **Total** | **18** | **18/18** |\n   494→\n   495→### Risk Assessment\n   496→\n   497→- **Dictionary-guided OCR repair** is the highest-risk change (new code path, could\n   498→  over-correct clean text). Mitigation: only trigger when word contains a known\n   499→  OCR-artifact character; dictionary match is a positive signal, not a filter.\n   500→\n   501→- **Compound title dedup protection** could allow over-long titles to survive. Mitigation:\n   502→  only protects titles with explicit ` : ` or ` + ` separators, which are intentional\n   503→  compound forms.\n   504→\n   505→- **Title-absent detection** could produce false negatives (return empty when title exists\n   506→  but is preceded by ingredient-like lines). Mitigation: only trigger when the *first 3*\n   507→  non-empty lines are all ingredients/instructions — rare for files that do have a title.\n   508→\n   509→- **Candidate-relative position bonus** changes scoring for all files, not just the 3\n   510→  failures. Mitigation: the bonus is additive to existing position factor, not a replacement.\n   511→  Files where position-0 candidate is correct (the common case) are unaffected because\n   512→  their first candidate is also position-0 in the raw array.\n   513→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015ygKBPCmwC1T2xezVmc3V5","session_id":"93fcd165-c384-4cf1-b48c-241fa9498df5","uuid":"a4501abe-3ecc-4a41-b2bc-82913012220a"}
