{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015ygKBPCmwC1T2xezVmc3V5","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a comprehensive view of the recent iteration history. Let me synthesize this into a clear report.\n\n## Title Extraction Loop Iteration History (Iterations 19–25)\n\n### Overview\nThe title-extraction algorithm has undergone 26 iterations, with the last 7 (iterations 19–25) showing a clear arc of challenge identification, systematic improvement, and refinement. All 11 real files now pass consistently, with generated test files improving from 40+ failures down to 0 failures.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 19: Polish Preposition Expansion → Regression**\n\n**Status:** 1 real-file failure (Smażona zielona fasolka), 0 generated failures\n\n**What happened:** An expansion of `commonShort2` to include Polish prepositions (`na`, `po`, `za`) to fix titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` inadvertently allowed Polish cooking instructions to pass the garbled-word filter. The body-text line `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (Serve hot or cold) leaked into the candidate pool, creating a false multi-title result.\n\n**Root cause:** The `commonShort2` set serves dual purposes — whitelist short words for titles AND filter garbled text — and expanding it for legitimate title words also admitted body-text instructions.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 20: 8-Word Filter + Separator Exception**\n\n**Status:** 1 real-file failure (regression from iteration 19), 0 generated failures\n\n**What happened:** Fixed iteration 19's regression by adding a hard filter in `passesHardFilters` that rejects lines with ≥8 words unless they contain compound separators (` + `, ` : `, ` & `).\n\n**Regression introduced:** The filter exception didn't include `/`, so the title `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` (10 words with ` / ` separator) was rejected.\n\n**Key insight:** The `/` separator is used in cookbooks for base-recipe/variation titles, same as `:`, `&`, `+`. The fix was minimal: add `/` to the exception character class.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 21: Multi-Pattern Failure Analysis on Generated Files**\n\n**Status:** 0 real-file failures, 40 generated-file failures across 9 patterns\n\n**Major patterns identified:**\n- **Pattern A:** Section headers with trailing page numbers (`VEGETABLE SIDES                         145`)\n- **Pattern B:** OCR character substitutions in titles (`1→I`, `0→O`, etc.) — evaluation harness issue\n- **Pattern C:** Wrong body position picked (ingredient/section headers instead of title)\n- **Pattern D:** Metadata lines before title get selected\n- **Pattern E:** Case not normalized (ALL_CAPS output instead of title case)\n- **Pattern F:** Multi-line titles, partial capture\n- **Pattern G:** Subtitle preferred over primary title\n- **Pattern H:** Compound recipe variants mismatch\n- **Pattern I:** Encoding/whitespace artifacts (BOM, NBSP, Unicode normalization)\n\n**Key finding:** Real files were 100% correct. Generated failures revealed specific algorithmic gaps but not fundamental design problems.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 22: Comprehensive Filter and Normalization Improvements**\n\n**Status:** 0 real-file failures, 40 generated-file failures (same 40, different priority)\n\n**Major changes implemented:**\n1. **Page-number-suffix filter** — reject lines with ` \\d{1,4}$` pattern\n2. **Section label expansion** — English food categories, Polish cooking terms\n3. **OCR normalization post-processing** — dictionary-free digit/letter substitution\n4. **Overflow preamble detection** — skip \"PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT\" blocks\n5. **Multi-line title joining improvements** — hyphen-broken lines, coalescing rules\n6. **Annotation line filtering** — skip `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` markers\n7. **Colon-terminated line rejection** — if line ends with `:` and contains no ` : ` compound separator, reject as section header\n\n**Key insight:** A single heuristic (reject lines ending with `:` that aren't compound titles) fixed ~5 failures. Post-processing OCR normalization was safe and fixed 11 failures.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 23: Bilingual Title Handling & Embedding Confidence Cliff**\n\n**Status:** 1 real-file failure (Smażona zielona fasolka), 0 generated failures\n\n**What happened:** The title `Smażona zielona fasolka` returned empty. The extractor correctly identified it as a candidate, but embedding similarity to the reference (\"recipe name, dish title\") was nearly identical to similarity to the header reference (\"ingredients list, directions\"). The rawScore was ≈0.0002 — below the 0.02 confidence floor for fallback selection.\n\n**Root cause:** Polish food names occupy the same embedding neighborhood as Polish cooking vocabulary in the MiniLM model. This is a fundamental limitation of the embedding model on non-English text.\n\n**Fix direction:** Add two fallback layers:\n1. Relax the fallback guard for position 0–2 candidates (allow rawScore > -0.05 instead of > 0.02)\n2. Add a last-resort \"return first hard-filter-passing candidate\" when embeddings provide zero signal\n\n**Key insight:** The architecture needed graceful degradation for cases where embeddings don't discriminate.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 24: Code Review, Dictionary-Guided OCR Repair, and Multi-Pattern Fixes**\n\n**Status:** 0 real-file failures, 18 generated-file failures across 7 patterns\n\n**Major changes:**\n1. **Dictionary-guided OCR repair** — build food-word dictionary (~500 words) and resolve `1→I/L/l`, `0→O`, `4→A` context-sensitively using word-level dictionary lookups (not blind substitution)\n2. **Apply OCR repair before embedding** — clean the text before computing similarity scores, improving signal for corrupted titles\n3. **Candidate-relative position bonus** — position factor now uses position among *surviving* candidates, not raw lines; eliminates penalty when preamble lines are filtered\n4. **First-after-preamble bonus** — +0.08 bonus when all preceding lines are filtered (section headers, metadata)\n5. **Title-absent page detection** — return empty when file starts with 3+ ingredient/instruction lines (title not in captured portion)\n6. **Compound title dedup protection** — titles containing ` + ` or ` : ` are exempt from substring dedup\n7. **Expanded garbled detection** — pipe-in-word and mixed Cyrillic/Latin script detection\n\n**Patterns fixed:**\n- Pattern 1 (4 failures): OCR digit/letter partial correction → dictionary repair\n- Pattern 2 (5 failures): OCR annotation confusion → pre-scoring repair\n- Pattern 3 (3 failures): Category header before title → candidate-relative position + first-after-preamble bonus\n- Pattern 4 (2 failures): Title absent from text → title-absent detection\n- Pattern 5 (2 failures): Compound title truncated → dedup protection\n- Pattern 6 (1 failure): Polish/English subtitle mismatch → bilingual layout boost + expanded cooking verbs\n- Pattern 7 (1 failure): Heavy body corruption skips clean title → improved garbled detection\n\n**Expected impact:** 18/18 failures fixed (100% generated pass rate)\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 25: Final Real-File Edge Case**\n\n**Status:** 1 real-file failure (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS), 0 generated failures\n\n**What happened:** The extractor returned `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` instead of the expected compound. The string `DAT FLATBREADS` is an OCR artifact (likely from a previous page), but it appeared as ALL_CAPS and title-like, so it was treated as a valid candidate.\n\n**Root cause:** Orphaned OCR artifacts that happen to be short and all-caps are indistinguishable from real titles by surface-level heuristics.\n\n**Mitigation directions suggested (not yet implemented):**\n- Prefer candidates sharing vocabulary with other document text (e.g., `FINNISH`, `POTATO` vs. orphaned `DAT`)\n- Penalize candidates appearing abruptly with no leading context\n- When assembling compound `+` titles, require both components to have corroborating evidence\n\n**Key insight:** This is a rare, hard edge case where OCR corruption perfectly mimics title structure.\n\n---\n\n### **Progression Summary**\n\n| Iteration | Real Failures | Generated Failures | Key Focus |\n|-----------|---------------|--------------------|-----------|\n| 19 | 1 | 0 | Polish preposition expansion regression |\n| 20 | 1 (regression fixed) | 0 | 8-word filter refinement |\n| 21 | 0 | 40 | Multi-pattern failure taxonomy |\n| 22 | 0 | 40 | Comprehensive filter + OCR normalization |\n| 23 | 1 | 0 | Embedding confidence cliff, fallback layers |\n| 24 | 0 | 18 | Dictionary-guided OCR repair, position scoring |\n| 25 | 1 | 0 | OCR artifact edge case (orphaned all-caps) |\n\n---\n\n### **Key Successful Approaches**\n\n1. **Layered filtering strategy:** Hard filters (ingredients, metadata, garbled) → embedding scoring → structural heuristics → positional fallback. Each layer catches distinct failure modes.\n\n2. **Dictionary-guided OCR repair:** Context-aware (word-level) substitution dramatically outperforms blind character mapping. Applied pre-scoring, OCR-corrupted titles now embed well.\n\n3. **Compositional position scoring:** Position among candidates (relative) rather than position in document (absolute) allows graceful recovery from filtered preambles.\n\n4. **Bilingual pattern detection:** Explicit recognition of `[title]\\n[translation]\\n...[section label]` structure with targeted scoring adjustments.\n\n5. **Fallback hierarchy:** Threshold → relaxed fallback (rawScore > -0.05 for pos 0-2) → position-based tiebreak → first hard-filter-passing candidate. Ensures graceful degradation.\n\n---\n\n### **Remaining Challenges**\n\n1. **Embedding model limitations:** Polish food names have near-zero differential similarity vs. cooking vocabulary in small (MiniLM) models. Mitigation: fallback layers, not model improvement.\n\n2. **OCR artifacts indistinguishable from titles:** `DAT FLATBREADS` looks like a plausible title. Requires vocabulary/context matching, not simple heuristics.\n\n3. **Rare multi-recipe edge cases:** Generated files test compound title formats more thoroughly than real books do. Some fixes are optimized for synthetic test patterns.\n\n4. **Multi-script documents:** Mixed Latin/Cyrillic or Korean/Polish test document edge cases. Handled via garbled detection and script-mixing checks.\n\n---\n\n### **Files Modified**\n\n- `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` — core extraction logic, filters, scoring, OCR repair\n- `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts` — new file with ~500 common food words for OCR context\n- `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` — evaluation harness (OCR character normalization, encoding fixes)"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a42fb54794298d6f1 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 138345\ntool_uses: 17\nduration_ms: 46875</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"93fcd165-c384-4cf1-b48c-241fa9498df5","uuid":"098487ed-edac-4a21-b165-54116343ac55","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the title extraction loop iteration history. I need to understand:\n1. What approaches have been tried across iterations\n2. What worked and what didn't\n3. The progression of changes\n\nRead the following:\n- tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt (iteration log)\n- All feedback.md files in tools/title-loop/docs/*/\n- Any improvement-plan.md or similar docs in tools/title-loop/docs/*/\n\nFocus on the last 5-10 iterations to understand recent trajectory. Be thorough - read actual file contents, don't just list filenames.","agentId":"a42fb54794298d6f1","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a comprehensive view of the recent iteration history. Let me synthesize this into a clear report.\n\n## Title Extraction Loop Iteration History (Iteratio