{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016WpEnpbx9B6f4UJHJrePCg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze the actual input file:\n\nLines 1-3: Garbled OCR text (clearly from a previous recipe's instructions - cut off mid-sentence)\nLine 4: \"DAT FLATBREADS\" - OCR artifact (likely \"OATMEAL FLATBREADS\" or similar, truncated)\nLines 5-14: Body text of the first recipe (the one DAT FLATBREADS belongs to)\nLine 16: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" - correct title #1\nLines 17-28: Body of Finnish Milk Flatbreads recipe\n\n\nLine 29: \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" - correct title #2\nLines 30-42: Body of Finnish Potato Flatbreads recipe\nLine 43: \"175 Recipes / Flatbreads\" - page footer\n\nSo the document has three ALL_CAPS candidates, but the extractor is picking up the corrupted \"DAT FLATBREADS\" along with the legitimate \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS,\" missing the third recipe entirely.\n\nThe issue is that the first few lines are spillover from the previous page—\"DAT FLATBREADS\" is probably a fragment of something like \"OATMEAL FLATBREADS.\" The multi-title logic finds multiple ALL_CAPS headings and keeps them, but it's grabbing the wrong pair. I need to trace through the logic: when there are two or more ALL_CAPS survivors, it sorts by position, then checks if the non-first ones are actually sub-headers by looking for ingredients below them. If they are, it should be filtering out the garbage entries and keeping the valid recipes.\n\nLooking at the actual content, both \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" and \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" are followed by their Finnish names and descriptions, then prep times, then ingredients—so they should pass the sub-header check. But the logic isn't filtering correctly, which means either the sub-header detection is failing or the filtering logic itself has a bug. at 3. But the feedback shows only 2 items in the result, so something's